istrations statistics the percapita energy consumption in the us has been somewhat consistent from the s to today the average has been  million british thermal units btus per person from  to  one explanation suggested for this is that the energy required to produce the increase in us consumption of manufactured equipment cars and other goods has been shifted to other countries producing and transporting those goods to the us with a corresponding shift of green house gases and pollution in comparison the world average has increased from  in  to  million btus per person in  on the other hand us offshoring of manufacturing is sometimes exaggerated us domestic manufacturing has grown by  since citation needed contents  history  current consumption  consumption by sector  consumption by source  regional variation  renewable energy  oil  price  consumption and production  policy  electrical energy  consumption  generation  trends  projections  energy consumption of computers in the usa  fossilfuel equivalency  international cooperation  see also  references  further reading  external links historyedit us energy consumption by source  vertical axis is in quadrillion btu from its founding until the late th century the united states was a largely agrarian country with abundant forests during this period energy consumption overwhelmingly focused on readily available firewood rapid industrialization of the economy urbanization and the growth of railroads led to increased use of coal and by  it had eclipsed wood as the nations primary energy source coal remained dominant for the next seven decades but by  it was surpassed in turn by both petroleum and natural gas in  coal consumption was the highest it has ever been with coal mostly being used to generate electricity natural gas which is cleanerburning and more easily transportable has replaced coal as the preferred source of heating in homes businesses and industrial furnaces although total energy use increased by approximately a factor of  between  and  energy use per capita increased only by a factor of four as of  united states per capita energy use had declined to  kilograms of oilequivalent  less than  and through  most recent available is at levels not seen since s usage levels at the beginning of the th century petroleum was a minor resource used to manufacture lubricants and fuel for kerosene and oil lamps one hundred years later it had become the preeminent energy source for the us and the rest of the world this rise closely paralleled the emergence of the automobile as a major force in american culture and the economy while petroleum is also used as a source for plastics and other chemicals and powers various industrial processes today twothirds of oil consumption in the us is in the form of its derived transportation fuels oils unique qualities for transportation fuels in terms of energy content cost of production and speed of refueling all contributed to it being used over other fuels in june  the american energy innovation council a group which includes bill gates founder of microsoft jeffrey r immelt chief executive of general electric and john doerr has urged the government to more than triple spending on energy research and development to  billion a year mr gates endorsed the administrations goal of reducing greenhouse gas emissions by  percent by  but said that was not possible with todays technology or politicism he said that the only way to find such disruptive new technology was to pour large sums of money at the problem the group notes that the federal government spends less than  billion a year on energy research and development not counting onetime stimulus projects about  billion is spent annually on health research and more than  billion on military r d they advocate a jump in spending on basic energy research us co emissions have dropped about  per year through greater efficiency and a sluggish economy since  current consumptionedit main article energy supply en